right upper lobe. <b>(c)</b> Axial CT image (mediastinal window) shows enlargement of the main pulmonary artery with a small pericardial effusion (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig14a.jpeg" height="1439" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span>. PH with congenital heart disease (group 1) in a patient with Eisenmenger syndrome secondary to an atrial septal defect. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image (mediastinal window) at the level of the main pulmonary artery shows marked enlargement of the pulmonary artery with a small mural thrombus (large arrow) and calcifications (small arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image (mediastinal window) through the lower lobes shows marked enlargement of the segmental and subsegmental pulmonary arteries and shunt reversal from the right atrium to the left atrium (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig14b.jpeg" height="1439" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span>. PH with congenital heart disease (group 1) in a patient with Eisenmenger syndrome secondary to an atrial septal defect. <b>(a)</b> Axial CT image (mediastinal window) at the level of the main pulmonary artery shows marked enlargement of the pulmonary artery with a small mural thrombus (large arrow) and calcifications (small arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial CT image (mediastinal window) through the lower lobes shows marked enlargement of the segmental and subsegmental pulmonary arteries and shunt reversal from the right atrium to the left atrium (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig15a.jpeg" height="1722" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span>. PH due to left heart disease (group 2) in a patient with mitral valve disease. Axial CT images (mediastinal window) at the level of the mitral valve <b>(a)</b> and main pulmonary artery <b>(b)</b> show marked calcification of the mitral valve and annulus (arrow in <b>a</b>) with severe PH and calcification of the pulmonary arteries (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig15b.jpeg" height="1722" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span>. PH due to left heart disease (group 2) in a patient with mitral valve disease. Axial CT images (mediastinal window) at the level of the mitral valve <b>(a)</b> and main pulmonary artery <b>(b)</b> show marked calcification of the mitral valve and annulus (arrow in <b>a</b>) with severe PH and calcification of the pulmonary arteries (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig16a.jpeg" height="1415" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span>. PH with congenital heart disease (group 1) in a patient with an interrupted right pulmonary artery. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images (mediastinal window) show absence of the right pulmonary artery (☆ in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) with hypertrophied bronchial arteries (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig16b.jpeg" height="1415" width="1775" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span>. PH with congenital heart disease (group 1) in a patient with an interrupted right pulmonary artery. Axial <b>(a, b)</b> and coronal <b>(c)</b> CT images (mediastinal window) show absence of the right pulmonary artery (☆ in <b>a</b> and <b>b</b>) with hypertrophied bronchial arteries (arrow in <b>a</b> and <b>c</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.2018170046&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.2018170046/asset/images/large/rg.2018170046.fig16c.jpeg" height="1355" width="1600" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><sp